WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.586 --> 00:00:08.336
(cheerful music)

00:00:22.344 --> 00:00:24.457
- I'd like to tell you
about some of the processes

00:00:24.457 --> 00:00:28.521
that unfold as the baby
brain grows and develops,

00:00:28.521 --> 00:00:30.683
in particular I'm gonna focus on

00:00:30.683 --> 00:00:32.601
the underpinnings of language,

00:00:32.601 --> 00:00:34.941
since language learning
impairment is a feature

00:00:34.941 --> 00:00:36.973
of so many developmental disorders,

00:00:36.973 --> 00:00:39.330
which we're gonna get into later.

00:00:39.330 --> 00:00:41.784
So why look at baby brain function?

00:00:41.784 --> 00:00:44.726
Because while we watch
this magical unfolding

00:00:44.726 --> 00:00:47.262
of early abilities across development,

00:00:47.262 --> 00:00:49.553
we can begin to answer
some very big questions,

00:00:49.553 --> 00:00:52.609
including how do early
events of development

00:00:52.609 --> 00:00:55.275
influence later cognition
and later competence?

00:00:55.275 --> 00:00:58.005
What risk factors during early development

00:00:58.005 --> 00:01:00.834
have consequences for
adult behavior or disorder

00:01:00.834 --> 00:01:03.743
and how that might, how
might that be altered,

00:01:03.743 --> 00:01:07.075
and how can very early
abnormalities in the functional

00:01:07.075 --> 00:01:09.968
organization of brain networks be causal

00:01:09.968 --> 00:01:11.854
in developmental disorders,

00:01:11.854 --> 00:01:16.194
such as language learning
disorder, autism, or ADHD.

00:01:16.194 --> 00:01:20.517
And importantly, how early
might biomarkers be detected,

00:01:20.517 --> 00:01:24.434
measured and perhaps
remediated with non-invasive

00:01:24.434 --> 00:01:25.517
technologies?

00:01:27.653 --> 00:01:30.611
So as newborns, babies can
discriminate the sounds

00:01:30.611 --> 00:01:34.778
of every language acoustically
but not linguistically.

00:01:36.121 --> 00:01:38.803
So starting at birth, the
baby's developing brain

00:01:38.803 --> 00:01:41.517
is constructing an
acoustic map of the sounds

00:01:41.517 --> 00:01:43.110
of his or her native language.

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:46.263
And this gradual process,
perceptual narrowing,

00:01:46.263 --> 00:01:49.726
is thought to be completed
by the end of the first year.

00:01:49.726 --> 00:01:52.521
Mapping of these acoustic
contrasts is important

00:01:52.521 --> 00:01:55.089
because their salient to
the surrounding language

00:01:55.089 --> 00:01:57.349
ultimately allows the
child to respond in a

00:01:57.349 --> 00:02:00.957
fast automatic way to the
incoming language stream,

00:02:00.957 --> 00:02:03.574
and it's problematic if
this doesn't go well.

00:02:03.574 --> 00:02:07.741
Because it impacts mounting
of fluent native language

00:02:08.905 --> 00:02:11.490
as well as cognition and later reading

00:02:11.490 --> 00:02:12.980
due to difficulties in what's called

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:15.336
phoneme to grapheme mapping,

00:02:15.336 --> 00:02:17.449
that is matching speech sounds to lens

00:02:17.449 --> 00:02:20.603
which you need to do to read.

00:02:20.603 --> 00:02:22.976
Efficient processing of
basic auditory events

00:02:22.976 --> 00:02:25.024
in the 10s of millisecond domain,

00:02:25.024 --> 00:02:27.153
called rapid auditory processing,

00:02:27.153 --> 00:02:30.192
is critical to mounting language
in normative development,

00:02:30.192 --> 00:02:32.452
and allows the most optimal acoustic maps

00:02:32.452 --> 00:02:33.866
to be constructed.

00:02:33.866 --> 00:02:35.816
And this is because many speech sounds,

00:02:35.816 --> 00:02:39.983
phonemes like "da" or "ta"
only differ by brief spectral

00:02:40.855 --> 00:02:42.952
and or temporal changes
specifically within

00:02:42.952 --> 00:02:44.658
the 10s of milliseconds.

00:02:44.658 --> 00:02:48.559
And differences in these basic
acoustic processing abilities

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:51.225
have been shown to be
related to both concurrent

00:02:51.225 --> 00:02:54.362
and later language learning difficulties.

00:02:54.362 --> 00:02:56.540
Research from my lab strongly suggests

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:59.206
that the ability to
perform these very fine

00:02:59.206 --> 00:03:02.424
acoustic discriminations
within speech or non-speech,

00:03:02.424 --> 00:03:05.951
because we mainly look at
pre-linguistic non-speech,

00:03:05.951 --> 00:03:08.633
is critically important
to normative language

00:03:08.633 --> 00:03:12.128
and it may go awry in a subset
of developmental disorders.

00:03:12.128 --> 00:03:14.826
Moreover, these skills
predict language outcomes

00:03:14.826 --> 00:03:17.199
through early pre-reading
and have an impact

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:18.711
on later learning.

00:03:18.711 --> 00:03:20.629
So many of our studies,

00:03:20.629 --> 00:03:23.327
we examine populations at higher risk

00:03:23.327 --> 00:03:26.057
for various disorders as
a consequence of a child

00:03:26.057 --> 00:03:29.438
being born into a family
with such disorders.

00:03:29.438 --> 00:03:31.828
And heritability to study suggest

00:03:31.828 --> 00:03:34.493
the risk can be 30 to 60% higher,

00:03:34.493 --> 00:03:37.988
depending on which
disorder and which study.

00:03:37.988 --> 00:03:41.856
So how do you measure
brain responses in infants?

00:03:41.856 --> 00:03:45.497
You can use eletroencephalography, EEG,

00:03:45.497 --> 00:03:48.080
which reflects the summation of

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:51.706
the synchronous activity
of millions of neurons

00:03:51.706 --> 00:03:54.177
that have similar spatial orientation.

00:03:54.177 --> 00:03:57.606
You can also use brain
invoked related potentials.

00:03:57.606 --> 00:04:00.223
And this is an average across many trials

00:04:00.223 --> 00:04:03.393
to generate an average
wave-form that is timelocked

00:04:03.393 --> 00:04:05.327
to external stimulation.

00:04:05.327 --> 00:04:08.253
This permits examination
of the time course

00:04:08.253 --> 00:04:11.552
in the brain areas related
to sensory processing,

00:04:11.552 --> 00:04:15.421
and you can compare and
contrast group response

00:04:15.421 --> 00:04:19.322
as well as compare individual
responses to group norms.

00:04:19.322 --> 00:04:22.020
Research suggests that brain oscillations,

00:04:22.020 --> 00:04:24.864
which are cyclic fluctuations
of the membrane potential

00:04:24.864 --> 00:04:27.839
in brain cells control
neuronal excitability,

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:29.497
integrate sensory inputs

00:04:29.497 --> 00:04:31.918
and may coordinate higher-level functions

00:04:31.918 --> 00:04:34.210
such as language, memory and learning.

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:37.331
However, neural dynamics whose
just beginning to be studied

00:04:37.331 --> 00:04:40.631
in the human infant, our
previous studies in pilot data

00:04:40.631 --> 00:04:43.540
strongly suggest that oscillatory dynamics

00:04:43.540 --> 00:04:45.621
and their hierarchical organization

00:04:45.621 --> 00:04:47.620
have a developmental timeline

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:52.496
and may capture disruption
in normative development.

00:04:52.496 --> 00:04:53.748
So how can you look at that?

00:04:53.748 --> 00:04:56.446
You can look at the EEG.

00:04:56.446 --> 00:04:59.241
And you can do something called
a fast foraying analysis,

00:04:59.241 --> 00:05:00.818
this is one way of doing it,

00:05:00.818 --> 00:05:03.568
which breaks the EEG pattern down

00:05:04.979 --> 00:05:08.230
into its component frequencies.

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:11.074
Synchronized neural oscillations
in these low frequencies,

00:05:11.074 --> 00:05:14.000
Delta, Theta and Alpha
are thought to provide

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.381
key mechanisms that orchestrate
network coordination

00:05:17.381 --> 00:05:19.770
during development, and may
be involved in information

00:05:19.770 --> 00:05:22.485
transfer among brain areas.

00:05:22.485 --> 00:05:24.435
Theta oscillations in particular

00:05:24.435 --> 00:05:27.474
are important for perceptual
and cognitive functions,

00:05:27.474 --> 00:05:30.319
such as declarative and episodic memory,

00:05:30.319 --> 00:05:32.806
and have been proposed
as a neural mechanism

00:05:32.806 --> 00:05:34.724
subserving phonemic discrimination,

00:05:34.724 --> 00:05:37.227
which is one of the reasons
we're very interested in it.

00:05:37.227 --> 00:05:40.852
Gamma oscillations from
30 to 80 or 90 Hertz

00:05:40.852 --> 00:05:43.306
may represent synchronized activity

00:05:43.306 --> 00:05:46.313
of local neuronal populations

00:05:46.313 --> 00:05:48.426
during sensory and cognitive processes,

00:05:48.426 --> 00:05:51.092
but may also, particularly high Gamma,

00:05:51.092 --> 00:05:54.554
play a role in coupling
of remote cortical areas.

00:05:54.554 --> 00:05:57.382
So given that activity
in this Gamma frequency

00:05:57.382 --> 00:05:59.527
has been linked in humans and animals

00:05:59.527 --> 00:06:02.274
to a wide variety of
higher cognitive processes,

00:06:02.274 --> 00:06:04.696
including attention, memory and language,

00:06:04.696 --> 00:06:08.288
we first examined power
density in frontal cortex

00:06:08.288 --> 00:06:11.750
across the language burst
in two groups of children.

00:06:11.750 --> 00:06:13.116
And I'm gonna give you
a few little snippets

00:06:13.116 --> 00:06:14.449
of some studies.

00:06:15.326 --> 00:06:20.024
We studied the power of spectra
in two groups of children

00:06:20.024 --> 00:06:21.698
with and without a family history

00:06:21.698 --> 00:06:23.404
of language learning impairment,

00:06:23.404 --> 00:06:26.151
at 16, 24 and 36 months of age,

00:06:26.151 --> 00:06:29.402
when this huge burst in language occurs.

00:06:29.402 --> 00:06:32.474
We found that individual
differences in frontal gamma power

00:06:32.474 --> 00:06:36.473
during rest highly correlated
with concurrent language

00:06:36.473 --> 00:06:39.154
and cognitive skills at all ages.

00:06:39.154 --> 00:06:40.666
Children with a family history

00:06:40.666 --> 00:06:41.901
of language learning impairment

00:06:41.901 --> 00:06:45.526
had lower frontal gamma at all ages.

00:06:45.526 --> 00:06:48.582
Power was also associated
with attentional measures,

00:06:48.582 --> 00:06:51.215
children who were observed as having

00:06:51.215 --> 00:06:53.312
better inhibitory control

00:06:53.312 --> 00:06:55.360
and more mature attention
shifting abilities

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:57.278
had higher power.

00:06:57.278 --> 00:06:59.569
We continued to follow this group

00:06:59.569 --> 00:07:02.121
and we found that examining gamma across

00:07:02.121 --> 00:07:03.991
the language burst strongly predicted

00:07:03.991 --> 00:07:08.158
to both cognition and language
at ages four and five years.

00:07:09.111 --> 00:07:12.111
We saw that at 16, 24 and 36 months,

00:07:14.393 --> 00:07:17.368
resting gamma was
associated with four year

00:07:17.368 --> 00:07:19.919
language comprehension scores

00:07:19.919 --> 00:07:23.999
and word structure and
sentence structure scores.

00:07:23.999 --> 00:07:26.112
And at 24 and 36 months,

00:07:26.112 --> 00:07:28.241
gamma power was significantly associated

00:07:28.241 --> 00:07:30.159
with five-year sentence imitation,

00:07:30.159 --> 00:07:32.500
which is really important for pre-readers,

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:36.011
36-month gamma power was
also significantly associated

00:07:36.011 --> 00:07:38.888
with five-year syntactical skills.

00:07:38.888 --> 00:07:40.973
So what's the take-home message here?

00:07:40.973 --> 00:07:45.422
We believe that the capacity
to generate higher power

00:07:45.422 --> 00:07:48.705
in the gamma range at these
crucial developmental periods

00:07:48.705 --> 00:07:51.615
may index better modulation of attention

00:07:51.615 --> 00:07:55.077
and allow easier access to working memory,

00:07:55.077 --> 00:07:58.279
providing an advantage
for overall development,

00:07:58.279 --> 00:08:00.944
particularly in the linguistic domain.

00:08:00.944 --> 00:08:02.619
We were then interested in examining

00:08:02.619 --> 00:08:04.894
oscillatory support in younger infants,

00:08:04.894 --> 00:08:08.642
so using event-related
potential, source localization

00:08:08.642 --> 00:08:12.241
and a time-frequency analysis
of event-related oscillations,

00:08:12.241 --> 00:08:15.833
so from source, we examined
the neural substrates

00:08:15.833 --> 00:08:19.279
of rapid auditory processing
in four-month-olds.

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:21.376
Animal models and adult experiments

00:08:21.376 --> 00:08:23.944
suggest that oscillatory synchrony,

00:08:23.944 --> 00:08:26.658
and in particular
low-frequency oscillations

00:08:26.658 --> 00:08:28.576
in the delta and theta range,

00:08:28.576 --> 00:08:31.486
play key roles in rapid
auditory processing

00:08:31.486 --> 00:08:33.664
and auditory change detection.

00:08:33.664 --> 00:08:36.232
So we hypothesized that
synchronized activity

00:08:36.232 --> 00:08:38.312
in brain oscillations in left and right

00:08:38.312 --> 00:08:40.734
auditory cortices would support

00:08:40.734 --> 00:08:43.562
rapid frequency discrimination in infants.

00:08:43.562 --> 00:08:47.236
Moreover, we thought that
infant perception of rapid pitch

00:08:47.236 --> 00:08:49.901
and timing changes, which is so critical,

00:08:49.901 --> 00:08:52.648
should be mediated in part at least

00:08:52.648 --> 00:08:55.184
by oscillatory mechanisms.

00:08:55.184 --> 00:08:57.736
These issues had not been
looked at in infants at all

00:08:57.736 --> 00:08:59.020
in human infants.

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:03.187
We used two sets of stimuli,
speech-like tones (beeping),

00:09:07.391 --> 00:09:09.308
and a control condition

00:09:10.641 --> 00:09:13.063
that was out of the speech-like range.

00:09:13.063 --> 00:09:15.355
So we found, this is a very busy slide,

00:09:15.355 --> 00:09:16.948
but I'll walk you through it.

00:09:16.948 --> 00:09:19.289
You're gonna see some of these figures

00:09:19.289 --> 00:09:22.832
that show pooled
oscillatory power over time,

00:09:22.832 --> 00:09:26.457
with frequency on the
x-axis, time on the y-axis

00:09:26.457 --> 00:09:29.496
for these complex tone
pairs in the control rate

00:09:29.496 --> 00:09:32.389
and in the rapid rate,
the speech-like rate.

00:09:32.389 --> 00:09:34.795
And these are for standards,
the background sounds,

00:09:34.795 --> 00:09:37.168
these are deviants, the ones that change,

00:09:37.168 --> 00:09:39.411
and this is the difference
between the two.

00:09:39.411 --> 00:09:41.752
Base synchronization is in red,

00:09:41.752 --> 00:09:43.930
desynchronization is in blue.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:48.838
And what we saw was that there
was enhanced phase-locking

00:09:48.838 --> 00:09:52.235
to variant tones in both rate conditions.

00:09:52.235 --> 00:09:55.161
Larger and faster activation
in the right hemisphere

00:09:55.161 --> 00:09:56.591
at both rates.

00:09:56.591 --> 00:09:59.631
However, left auditory
activity was enhanced

00:09:59.631 --> 00:10:02.882
only during Rapid Rate presentation.

00:10:02.882 --> 00:10:06.766
We also gave these babies
a go/no-go behavioral task

00:10:06.766 --> 00:10:08.652
at their second visit.

00:10:08.652 --> 00:10:11.464
Auditory perception was
measured by the infant's ability

00:10:11.464 --> 00:10:15.544
to learn a reward contingency
for a deviant tone in a pair,

00:10:15.544 --> 00:10:17.592
and the number of trials it took the baby

00:10:17.592 --> 00:10:21.590
to get four out of five
correct was their criterion.

00:10:21.590 --> 00:10:25.507
And we did a median split with
faster and slower learners

00:10:25.507 --> 00:10:28.287
and what you see is
that tone discrimination

00:10:28.287 --> 00:10:31.456
is strongest for the
children who learn faster.

00:10:31.456 --> 00:10:33.374
We also saw that slower learners

00:10:33.374 --> 00:10:35.325
had smaller power differences

00:10:35.325 --> 00:10:38.770
between their standard
and deviant responses.

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:42.785
And this is, suggests that
they had a lot of difficulty

00:10:42.785 --> 00:10:45.613
discriminating one signal from another.

00:10:45.613 --> 00:10:47.873
So the take away message here is that

00:10:47.873 --> 00:10:50.408
local low frequency oscillatory synchrony

00:10:50.408 --> 00:10:53.740
underlies rapid processing
and can robustly index

00:10:53.740 --> 00:10:56.244
auditory abilities in young infants.

00:10:56.244 --> 00:10:58.454
And recruitment of the left hemisphere

00:10:58.454 --> 00:11:01.526
during rapid frequency change
suggests a difference in the

00:11:01.526 --> 00:11:03.607
spectral and temporal resolution

00:11:03.607 --> 00:11:05.069
of the right and left hemispheres,

00:11:05.069 --> 00:11:07.312
even at this very early age.

00:11:07.312 --> 00:11:10.124
Moreover, we were able to predict behavior

00:11:10.124 --> 00:11:14.871
in a go/no-go task by looking
at oscillatory brain power.

00:11:14.871 --> 00:11:16.870
So the question is if we can find deficits

00:11:16.870 --> 00:11:19.243
so early in life, can we alter them

00:11:19.243 --> 00:11:21.567
using the exquisite plasticity typical

00:11:21.567 --> 00:11:23.892
of this early developmental time period,

00:11:23.892 --> 00:11:27.467
while infants are setting
up their acoustic mapping?

00:11:27.467 --> 00:11:29.499
Can we make the baby a better processor

00:11:29.499 --> 00:11:32.685
and can we see
intervention-specific changes

00:11:32.685 --> 00:11:35.188
in the brain waves and
oscillatory patterns

00:11:35.188 --> 00:11:37.821
that reflect enhanced processing?

00:11:37.821 --> 00:11:40.617
So can we look for some causal mechanisms?

00:11:40.617 --> 00:11:43.169
And so we did a study, we
did a couple of studies,

00:11:43.169 --> 00:11:46.046
and looking at plasticity
in developing brain

00:11:46.046 --> 00:11:48.451
and seeing if active auditory exposure

00:11:48.451 --> 00:11:51.848
would impact prelinguistic
acoustic mapping.

00:11:51.848 --> 00:11:54.091
And I'm gonna go through
this pretty quickly,

00:11:54.091 --> 00:11:57.310
but the paper's published if you need it.

00:11:57.310 --> 00:12:00.268
So we looked at the neural
correlates of acoustic mapping

00:12:00.268 --> 00:12:03.210
with dense array EEG/ERP before and after

00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:07.013
a six-week interactive,
progressive acoustic experience.

00:12:07.013 --> 00:12:10.713
We used a operantly-conditioned
go/no-go active paradigm

00:12:10.713 --> 00:12:12.182
with an eye-tracking control,

00:12:12.182 --> 00:12:16.349
so the baby could actually
manipulate the experiment.

00:12:17.822 --> 00:12:20.390
And we used a passive control

00:12:20.390 --> 00:12:23.072
and a naive maturation control.

00:12:23.072 --> 00:12:24.145
And here's the study design,

00:12:24.145 --> 00:12:27.266
two longitudinal arms,
one with active training,

00:12:27.266 --> 00:12:29.054
one with passive training,

00:12:29.054 --> 00:12:32.126
and two, a cross-sectional sample

00:12:32.126 --> 00:12:34.613
of children who were not trained.

00:12:34.613 --> 00:12:37.002
So what did they get
when they were trained?

00:12:37.002 --> 00:12:40.496
Once a week for six weeks,
for six to eight minutes,

00:12:40.496 --> 00:12:42.609
the babies were trained
on three different types

00:12:42.609 --> 00:12:46.120
of paired stimuli, complex
tones, bandpass noise,

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:49.469
frequency sweeps presented at varying ISIs

00:12:49.469 --> 00:12:51.062
and varying complexities,

00:12:51.062 --> 00:12:53.418
using an up-down staircase procedure.

00:12:53.418 --> 00:12:55.434
So if the baby got it
right, it got harder,

00:12:55.434 --> 00:12:57.319
they got it wrong, it got easier,

00:12:57.319 --> 00:13:00.229
and so they went up and down
until they reached criterion.

00:13:00.229 --> 00:13:02.391
The passive group got the same stimuli

00:13:02.391 --> 00:13:06.145
and the same time exposure,
but passive with no feedback,

00:13:06.145 --> 00:13:08.811
and we didn't train the naive children.

00:13:08.811 --> 00:13:10.804
After they were trained,

00:13:10.804 --> 00:13:13.387
we collected data on ERPs, EEGs

00:13:14.332 --> 00:13:16.413
that they had been trained on,

00:13:16.413 --> 00:13:20.948
as well as different types
of generalization stimuli,

00:13:20.948 --> 00:13:25.115
so we looked at deviants with
spectral temporal parameters

00:13:26.669 --> 00:13:29.221
that significantly differed
from the training stimuli,

00:13:29.221 --> 00:13:31.691
one with the gap, one with
the differing duration,

00:13:31.691 --> 00:13:34.227
and one with frequency.

00:13:34.227 --> 00:13:35.105
So what did we see?

