about these time-locked
age appropriate topograms

00:13:47.133 --> 00:13:49.633
to first of all, this P2 peak.

00:13:50.709 --> 00:13:52.415
And this is a peak that happens

00:13:52.415 --> 00:13:54.658
that's an attentional peak.

00:13:54.658 --> 00:13:58.819
And what we see here is
around each topogram,

00:13:58.819 --> 00:14:01.192
if it has a red box, it
means there was significantly

00:14:01.192 --> 00:14:02.948
faster latencies.

00:14:02.948 --> 00:14:05.776
So the active group was
significantly faster

00:14:05.776 --> 00:14:09.943
than both the passive and the
naive groups on this peak.

00:14:11.741 --> 00:14:13.935
And then we also were
interested in looking at

00:14:13.935 --> 00:14:16.227
what's called the N2 star.

00:14:16.227 --> 00:14:18.178
And this is the change discrimination peak

00:14:18.178 --> 00:14:21.315
that happens right before
the baby discriminates

00:14:21.315 --> 00:14:22.232
the signal.

00:14:23.347 --> 00:14:27.394
And it's important because
it's been shown to be

00:14:27.394 --> 00:14:31.311
a robust infant predictor
of later language.

00:14:31.311 --> 00:14:35.472
So both of the auditory
groups, experienced groups,

00:14:35.472 --> 00:14:38.511
were significantly faster
than the naive controls,

00:14:38.511 --> 00:14:40.755
but the actives had a larger amplitude

00:14:40.755 --> 00:14:43.258
compared to both other groups

00:14:43.258 --> 00:14:46.925
and showed a left
hemisphere lateralization.

00:14:49.402 --> 00:14:52.652
We then looked at the signals that were

00:14:53.595 --> 00:14:54.835
generalization stimuli,

00:14:54.835 --> 00:14:56.846
and what you can see in these bar graphs

00:14:56.846 --> 00:14:59.008
is mean latency of each deviant

00:14:59.008 --> 00:15:01.527
at each of the nine electrode sites.

00:15:01.527 --> 00:15:04.892
For P1, that's the first
sensory peak that signals

00:15:04.892 --> 00:15:07.232
that a stimulus has been perceived.

00:15:07.232 --> 00:15:10.207
And what you can see here for the gap,

00:15:10.207 --> 00:15:12.482
for the duration and the frequency is,

00:15:12.482 --> 00:15:15.554
the active group was significantly faster

00:15:15.554 --> 00:15:18.708
at all nine electrode sites.

00:15:18.708 --> 00:15:22.982
So we demonstrated that
while both active and passive

00:15:22.982 --> 00:15:26.136
acoustic experience from
four to seven months

00:15:26.136 --> 00:15:27.972
modulated non-speech stimuli,

00:15:27.972 --> 00:15:31.955
active experience conferred
a significant advantage,

00:15:31.955 --> 00:15:34.328
that active experience increased attention

00:15:34.328 --> 00:15:37.205
to environmental acoustic stimuli,

00:15:37.205 --> 00:15:39.740
and that faster latencies were seen

00:15:39.740 --> 00:15:41.561
for the change discrimination peak

00:15:41.561 --> 00:15:44.064
that has been shown to be
a robust infant predictor

00:15:44.064 --> 00:15:45.445
of later language.

00:15:45.445 --> 00:15:48.534
Moreover, we saw a
generalization to both trained

00:15:48.534 --> 00:15:51.118
and untrained stimuli
over and above that seen

00:15:51.118 --> 00:15:52.868
for maturation alone.

00:15:53.946 --> 00:15:57.489
And do these intervention
effects generalize to language?

00:15:57.489 --> 00:15:59.700
I can just say yes because I think

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:01.407
we're just about at the end,

00:16:01.407 --> 00:16:03.699
but just let me show you this high gamma

00:16:03.699 --> 00:16:07.453
at nine months, we can
look at them longitudinally

00:16:07.453 --> 00:16:09.160
and you can see that for the actives,

00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:12.394
you have this very high gamma input here,

00:16:12.394 --> 00:16:14.247
which is a prominent characteristic

00:16:14.247 --> 00:16:16.214
of early sensory processing

00:16:16.214 --> 00:16:18.408
and may index cortical activation,

00:16:18.408 --> 00:16:21.903
given larger high but
not low gamma responses

00:16:21.903 --> 00:16:25.739
are correlated with increases
in overall firing rates,

00:16:25.739 --> 00:16:29.526
particularly during
attentional modulation.

00:16:29.526 --> 00:16:32.143
And with that, I'll show you our prototype

00:16:32.143 --> 00:16:36.310
that does the same intervention
in the baby's home.

00:16:39.425 --> 00:16:40.258
And that's the end.

00:16:40.258 --> 00:16:42.919
(applauding)

00:16:42.919 --> 00:16:45.666
- So yeah, I wanna, I
really wanna follow on

00:16:45.666 --> 00:16:49.388
in this wonderful vein
of discussion and thought

00:16:49.388 --> 00:16:52.152
that we've had so far this, today.

00:16:52.152 --> 00:16:54.660
Thinking about this question,
making an brain young,

00:16:54.660 --> 00:16:56.930
as I get older, I want to be younger.

00:16:56.930 --> 00:17:00.181
So this is part of it, but
I really wanna consider

00:17:00.181 --> 00:17:04.407
how we can take lessons from understanding

00:17:04.407 --> 00:17:07.398
the child's brain and
see if we can apply them

00:17:07.398 --> 00:17:10.031
to the adult brain or the aging brain

00:17:10.031 --> 00:17:14.631
or the neural, the brain
with neuralpathology.

00:17:14.631 --> 00:17:17.849
And so first before I actually do that,

00:17:17.849 --> 00:17:19.932
I really wanna talk about

00:17:20.921 --> 00:17:24.269
the concept of what a critical period is,

00:17:24.269 --> 00:17:26.675
and just remind you that

00:17:26.675 --> 00:17:28.723
a developmental critical period

00:17:28.723 --> 00:17:31.600
is a period during which time

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:34.769
its special experiences are essential

00:17:34.769 --> 00:17:37.581
for the later functioning of the brain,

00:17:37.581 --> 00:17:40.426
and that's because these
experiences are essential

00:17:40.426 --> 00:17:42.263
for tuning up brain circuits,

00:17:42.263 --> 00:17:45.270
and I wanna talk about that in
much more detail in a minute,

00:17:45.270 --> 00:17:48.439
but a good example of a
developmental critical period

00:17:48.439 --> 00:17:50.357
that I've experienced alas myself

00:17:50.357 --> 00:17:52.226
is one for language learning.

00:17:52.226 --> 00:17:53.770
Obviously you can learn throughout life,

00:17:53.770 --> 00:17:56.090
you can learn languages
just throughout life.

00:17:56.090 --> 00:17:59.508
But learning a language
without an accent as an adult

00:17:59.508 --> 00:18:02.466
is extremely difficult,
whereas we all know now,

00:18:02.466 --> 00:18:06.010
it's extremely easy to learn
many languages perfectly

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:08.009
as a young child.

00:18:08.009 --> 00:18:10.756
And this has been my regret my whole life.

00:18:10.756 --> 00:18:13.763
Now how, so here's the concept, basically,

00:18:13.763 --> 00:18:16.932
which is if we could only understand

00:18:16.932 --> 00:18:19.760
the underlying molecular
and cellular mechanisms

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:22.881
that regulate these
developmental critical periods,

00:18:22.881 --> 00:18:24.653
maybe we could then apply them.

00:18:24.653 --> 00:18:26.555
Either in aid of repair,

00:18:26.555 --> 00:18:29.513
to reverse developmental neuropathology,

00:18:29.513 --> 00:18:31.496
or maybe even as a cognitive enhancer,

00:18:31.496 --> 00:18:34.633
so I could learn French for
example without an accent.

00:18:34.633 --> 00:18:38.127
Now in trying to
understand how this works,

00:18:38.127 --> 00:18:42.158
obviously at the level
of molecules and cells

00:18:42.158 --> 00:18:44.792
we really need to get into the brain,

00:18:44.792 --> 00:18:48.400
and it's possible to
do this in mice models.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:51.163
And in fact, mice as far as I know,

00:18:51.163 --> 00:18:54.755
have not been learning
second or third languages.

00:18:54.755 --> 00:18:58.868
But mice, just like us,
have binocular vision.

00:18:58.868 --> 00:19:01.111
So here's the question.

00:19:01.111 --> 00:19:03.955
Have you ever thought about
why it is you don't see double?

00:19:03.955 --> 00:19:06.621
I mean, what's happening
right is you have two eyes

00:19:06.621 --> 00:19:10.001
and each eye is sending a
complete view of the visual world

00:19:10.001 --> 00:19:13.594
to your brain, and yet, we
only see one view of the world

00:19:13.594 --> 00:19:15.707
unless there's some pathology.

00:19:15.707 --> 00:19:18.193
And one of the reasons
that we don't see double

00:19:18.193 --> 00:19:22.403
is because in fact, the
neuro circuitry for vision

00:19:22.403 --> 00:19:26.223
brings the connections
from the two eyes together

00:19:26.223 --> 00:19:28.807
in the central part of
the visual pathways.

00:19:28.807 --> 00:19:31.766
And let me just show you
a very simplified diagram

00:19:31.766 --> 00:19:32.806
of that now.

00:19:32.806 --> 00:19:36.951
So the point is, that the
output neurons from the eyes,

00:19:36.951 --> 00:19:39.275
these RGCs, the ganglion cells,

00:19:39.275 --> 00:19:44.119
send their connections to
central structures, like the LGN

00:19:44.119 --> 00:19:47.191
and then beyond that from the LGN

00:19:47.191 --> 00:19:48.735
to the primary visual cortex,

00:19:48.735 --> 00:19:51.644
so vision doesn't happen,
visual perception doesn't happen

00:19:51.644 --> 00:19:53.513
in your eye, it happens in your brain.

00:19:53.513 --> 00:19:56.634
And so these first few
steps you can see already

00:19:56.634 --> 00:20:00.047
how the wiring is bringing
the two eyes together.

00:20:00.047 --> 00:20:03.054
So for example, one of these RGCs here

00:20:03.054 --> 00:20:06.598
is sending its connection
across to this LGN,

00:20:06.598 --> 00:20:10.060
another one from the other
eye is sending its connection,

00:20:10.060 --> 00:20:12.222
and already you can see
that the information

00:20:12.222 --> 00:20:14.757
from the two eyes is
beginning to be combined,

00:20:14.757 --> 00:20:18.252
and then at the next stage
in information processing,

00:20:18.252 --> 00:20:21.470
that information is
again even more combined,

00:20:21.470 --> 00:20:26.015
in fact there's a rather
beautiful, in this case,

00:20:26.015 --> 00:20:28.481
left eye, right eye, left eye, right eye,

00:20:28.481 --> 00:20:31.165
left eye, right eye kind of
intermixing of the inputs

00:20:31.165 --> 00:20:34.736
from the two eyes and actually
those intermixed inputs

00:20:34.736 --> 00:20:38.008
make connections finally with
these little gray circles

00:20:38.008 --> 00:20:40.722
and these connections
are the target neurons

00:20:40.722 --> 00:20:44.477
that fall off, become the basis
for your binocular vision,

00:20:44.477 --> 00:20:45.631
in other words they're getting input

00:20:45.631 --> 00:20:48.085
from both the right eye and the left eye.

00:20:48.085 --> 00:20:51.385
Now before I go further, I
wanna define more what I mean

00:20:51.385 --> 00:20:53.563
about connections, I'm
talking about connections,

00:20:53.563 --> 00:20:56.554
but what I really mean
in neuroscience terms

00:20:56.554 --> 00:21:00.016
is synapses, the synapse,
what is a synapse,

00:21:00.016 --> 00:21:02.226
so let me just define a synapse.

00:21:02.226 --> 00:21:05.119
A synapse is the junction or connection

00:21:05.119 --> 00:21:08.988
between one neuron and the
next neuron along the line,

00:21:08.988 --> 00:21:10.873
passing information and by the way

00:21:10.873 --> 00:21:15.863
also doing some computations
as the information is passed.

00:21:15.863 --> 00:21:18.821
And in fact, you are your synapses.

00:21:18.821 --> 00:21:21.926
What I mean by that is
your synapses get tuned up

00:21:21.926 --> 00:21:24.332
during developmental critical periods,

00:21:24.332 --> 00:21:27.842
and even if you are genetically
identical to your sister,

00:21:27.842 --> 00:21:30.020
your twin or whatever, in fact,

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:32.052
your brain synapses are different

00:21:32.052 --> 00:21:34.767
because the pattern of
tuning is slightly different

00:21:34.767 --> 00:21:36.473
in each case.

00:21:36.473 --> 00:21:38.050
So you are your synapses.

00:21:38.050 --> 00:21:40.927
Synapses change with learning.

00:21:40.927 --> 00:21:43.430
Memories are stored at synapses.

00:21:43.430 --> 00:21:47.916
And sadly, in Alzheimer's
disease, synapses are lost,

00:21:47.916 --> 00:21:51.589
and so let's just remember
that as I talk further.

00:21:51.589 --> 00:21:53.756
Now what's amazing is that

00:21:55.182 --> 00:21:59.349
in animal models, it's
possible to visualize synapses.

00:22:00.887 --> 00:22:04.934
So we can go down to the
level of just a few microns

00:22:04.934 --> 00:22:07.925
and actually see and test synapses

00:22:07.925 --> 00:22:10.558
and understand how they
work in the animal models,

00:22:10.558 --> 00:22:14.670
like in the mice or
even in higher mammals.

00:22:14.670 --> 00:22:17.011
And many years ago this
experiment was done,

00:22:17.011 --> 00:22:19.953
and it's actually possible to visualize

00:22:19.953 --> 00:22:22.456
this really beautiful left eye, right eye,

00:22:22.456 --> 00:22:25.536
left eye, right eye, left
eye, right eye pattern

00:22:25.536 --> 00:22:29.022
of synapses in the visual cortex,

00:22:29.022 --> 00:22:32.289
and I just wanna show you
a very famous picture now

00:22:32.289 --> 00:22:34.955
from David Hubel and Torsten Wiesel's lab.

00:22:34.955 --> 00:22:37.296
And at this scale, let me just point out

00:22:37.296 --> 00:22:41.379
that these white blobs
over here on the left are,

00:22:42.448 --> 00:22:43.862
they're supposed to be grains of rice,

00:22:43.862 --> 00:22:45.829
so this gives you some sense of scale,

00:22:45.829 --> 00:22:48.037
those are grains of rice,

00:22:48.037 --> 00:22:51.403
and here you see one eye,
let's say the right eye,

00:22:51.403 --> 00:22:55.207
was labeled with a white tracer substance

00:22:55.207 --> 00:22:57.856
that gets all the way to the visual cortex

00:22:57.856 --> 00:23:02.375
and labels all the synapses
that are functionally connected

00:23:02.375 --> 00:23:05.008
to the white right eye.

00:23:05.008 --> 00:23:07.706
And so you can see, what I
told you that there's this

00:23:07.706 --> 00:23:10.778
beautiful right eye, left
eye, right eye, left eye,

00:23:10.778 --> 00:23:13.005
right eye, left eye striping pattern.

00:23:13.005 --> 00:23:15.340
And at this scale, what
you're looking at really is

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:19.165
hundreds of thousands of
these synapses at this scale,

00:23:19.165 --> 00:23:21.749
where every little dot is
about the size of a synapse.

00:23:21.749 --> 00:23:24.464
Now when neuroscientists first discovered

00:23:24.464 --> 00:23:28.544
this beautiful striping pattern
of synaptic connections,

00:23:28.544 --> 00:23:30.754
they thought it had to be hard-wired,

00:23:30.754 --> 00:23:32.895
it's much too beautiful,
much too reproducible

00:23:32.895 --> 00:23:34.915
to be left to chance.

00:23:34.915 --> 00:23:37.126
But in fact it turns out

00:23:37.126 --> 00:23:41.417
that during post-natal,
critical period of development,

00:23:41.417 --> 00:23:44.781
this pattern has to be
tuned up, in other words,

00:23:44.781 --> 00:23:48.861
even using both eyes
together for binocular vision

00:23:48.861 --> 00:23:51.901
requires an experienced dependent period.

00:23:51.901 --> 00:23:54.989
And in fact, one way
that this was discovered

00:23:54.989 --> 00:23:57.492
is in trying to understand
what's different between

00:23:57.492 --> 00:23:58.906
childhood cataract

00:23:58.906 --> 00:24:01.442
and cataract that you
might get as an adult,

00:24:01.442 --> 00:24:03.148
or your grandmother might get as an adult,

00:24:03.148 --> 00:24:06.139
where if you have normal
vision your whole life,

00:24:06.139 --> 00:24:10.024
and then you lose vision in one
eye for some period of time,

00:24:10.024 --> 00:24:12.153
when the optics are corrected,

00:24:12.153 --> 00:24:14.819
then you can see again
perfectly as an adult,

00:24:14.819 --> 00:24:18.151
and that's because these
beautiful stripes are stable.

00:24:18.151 --> 00:24:21.434
However, during a developmental period,

00:24:21.434 --> 00:24:24.197
these stripes are not stable,
they're getting tuned up.

00:24:24.197 --> 00:24:26.944
And if a child has a congenital cataract

00:24:26.944 --> 00:24:30.195
that's not corrected
early on in development,

00:24:30.195 --> 00:24:34.031
then the eye that's good gets way more

00:24:34.031 --> 00:24:36.176
than its fair share of territory,

00:24:36.176 --> 00:24:39.915
so way more white synapses
in the visual cortex

00:24:39.915 --> 00:24:42.174
than the bad eye gets.

00:24:42.174 --> 00:24:45.929
And the bad eye actually
loses synaptic connections,

00:24:45.929 --> 00:24:48.058
in fact those connections are pruned

00:24:48.058 --> 00:24:52.642
and Jay referred to this, I
think several of our previous

00:24:52.642 --> 00:24:54.885
speakers talked about
this idea of a period

00:24:54.885 --> 00:24:56.819
when there's a lot of synaptic remodeling

00:24:56.819 --> 00:24:58.802
and pruning going on.

00:24:58.802 --> 00:25:01.386
And that's what I wanna
really talk about now.

00:25:01.386 --> 00:25:03.597
So let me just summarize by saying,

00:25:03.597 --> 00:25:06.132
what you see now before your
eyes is a really beautiful

00:25:06.132 --> 00:25:10.131
example of synaptic plasticity, that is

00:25:10.131 --> 00:25:13.691
the ability of a neural
circuit to change its pattern

00:25:13.691 --> 00:25:16.031
of connections based on use.

00:25:16.031 --> 00:25:18.697
And this is an experience
dependent change,

00:25:18.697 --> 00:25:21.785
and in this case, it happens
only during a developmental

00:25:21.785 --> 00:25:23.638
critical period in the sense that

00:25:23.638 --> 00:25:25.556
after the critical period is over,

00:25:25.556 --> 00:25:27.962
which in us is around the age of six,

00:25:27.962 --> 00:25:30.660
these connections become stable

00:25:30.660 --> 00:25:33.862
and they can't change this
dramatically at later ages

00:25:33.862 --> 00:25:37.069
which is why grandma can see
even after having a cataract

00:25:37.069 --> 00:25:39.827
for a long period of
time, whereas the child,

00:25:39.827 --> 00:25:42.996
if the cataract isn't fixed quite soon,

00:25:42.996 --> 00:25:46.003
will be permanently blind in
the eye that was not used.

00:25:46.003 --> 00:25:48.913
So this is a real use it
or lose it kind of thing.

00:25:48.913 --> 00:25:52.034
So let me just summarize
here again by saying then

00:25:52.034 --> 00:25:55.918
that the baby's brain, just
like the adolescence brain,

00:25:55.918 --> 00:25:59.120
is not a miniature version
of the adult brain.

00:25:59.120 --> 00:26:01.623
It's a dynamically changing structure.

00:26:01.623 --> 00:26:03.671
And part of the change that's happening,

00:26:03.671 --> 00:26:05.589
and we can see it in the animal models,

00:26:05.589 --> 00:26:08.044
like mice for example,
is that there's this

00:26:08.044 --> 00:26:11.376
synaptic remodeling,
so synaptic plasticity

00:26:11.376 --> 00:26:14.627
is the basis for these
developmental critical periods,

00:26:14.627 --> 00:26:16.252
and during this time,

00:26:16.252 --> 00:26:20.754
many immature synapses,
the ones that are used

00:26:20.754 --> 00:26:23.290
get strengthened and stabilized,

00:26:23.290 --> 00:26:26.281
and the ones that are not are pruned away.

00:26:26.281 --> 00:26:29.244
So there's a kind of pruning
versus a growth period.

00:26:29.244 --> 00:26:33.156
So now, the question is, how
in the world does this work?

00:26:33.156 --> 00:26:36.505
How is this happening and if
we could only understand it,

00:26:36.505 --> 00:26:39.723
we could restore plasticity
maybe to the adult brain,

00:26:39.723 --> 00:26:41.933
but in order to do it,
really have to understand

00:26:41.933 --> 00:26:44.762
what are the underlying
molecules and mechanisms

00:26:44.762 --> 00:26:46.972
that actually are
responsible for this kind of

00:26:46.972 --> 00:26:48.630
pruning process.

00:26:48.630 --> 00:26:51.702
So for many, many years
ago, we worked very hard

00:26:51.702 --> 00:26:54.709
to discover molecules that
might be involved in pruning.

00:26:54.709 --> 00:26:57.342
And I wanna tell you about one.

00:26:57.342 --> 00:26:59.634
So this molecule is a big mouthful.

00:26:59.634 --> 00:27:01.812
It's called PirB.

00:27:01.812 --> 00:27:06.477
It's called paired
immunoglobulin-like receptor B.

00:27:06.477 --> 00:27:08.899
And it's very cool that it's a receptor.

00:27:08.899 --> 00:27:10.930
The reason I emphasize that is because

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:13.807
if you have a receptor, it
can be targeted for a drug

00:27:13.807 --> 00:27:16.083
or a pill, as I said
this is like my dream,

00:27:16.083 --> 00:27:19.355
but we're not there yet, but
it's good that it's a receptor.

00:27:19.355 --> 00:27:23.316
And the question is, how can
we show that this molecule

00:27:23.316 --> 00:27:26.437
is actually involved in plasticity?

00:27:26.437 --> 00:27:30.305
So one way that it's
possible in a mouse anyhow,

00:27:30.305 --> 00:27:33.296
is, well first of all I
should say that this molecule

00:27:33.296 --> 00:27:36.270
is present in the brain,
it's in the neurons,

00:27:36.270 --> 00:27:38.757
happily it's in our
favorite parts of the brain

00:27:38.757 --> 00:27:40.594
that we like to study all the time.

00:27:40.594 --> 00:27:42.577
The visual cortex in the mouse

00:27:42.577 --> 00:27:44.576
and the hippocampus in the mouse.

00:27:44.576 --> 00:27:45.828
So it's there.

00:27:45.828 --> 00:27:48.412
Now how can we actually
study its function?

00:27:48.412 --> 00:27:50.216
Well in mice,

00:27:50.216 --> 00:27:53.256
it's possible to remove
that particular molecule

00:27:53.256 --> 00:27:55.759
by taking away just that gene

00:27:55.759 --> 00:27:57.531
from the whole genome of the mouse,

00:27:57.531 --> 00:27:59.286
so there're 30,000 genes or so,

00:27:59.286 --> 00:28:01.285
and one can remove just that gene

00:28:01.285 --> 00:28:05.007
and from the very beginning
of development for instance,

00:28:05.007 --> 00:28:09.591
so we can make what's known
as a PirB gene knockout.

00:28:09.591 --> 00:28:12.403
And we can then either remove the gene

00:28:12.403 --> 00:28:14.061
from the very beginning of development,

00:28:14.061 --> 00:28:16.791
or if we're really fancy we
can take it away at any time

00:28:16.791 --> 00:28:21.148
of life and then we can
test is this gene needed

00:28:21.148 --> 00:28:23.326
for whatever, synaptic plasticity.

00:28:23.326 --> 00:28:26.024
And the bottom line
is, what we discovered,

00:28:26.024 --> 00:28:29.973
is that in fact, in these gene knockouts,

00:28:29.973 --> 00:28:33.501
in fact there is not
always the gene needed,

00:28:33.501 --> 00:28:36.313
but there's actually
more synaptic plasticity

00:28:36.313 --> 00:28:39.092
than normal, and I'm happy
to talk about this later,

00:28:39.092 --> 00:28:40.604
but just take my word for it,

00:28:40.604 --> 00:28:44.196
PirB is needed for synaptic plasticity.

00:28:44.196 --> 00:28:46.487
And so then we asked
how is this happening,

00:28:46.487 --> 00:28:48.552
what is actually going on?

00:28:48.552 --> 00:28:52.063
And you already know the
answer because I told you.

00:28:52.063 --> 00:28:55.330
I told you that during
that synaptic plasticity

00:28:55.330 --> 00:28:57.865
involves both pruning and strengthening

00:28:57.865 --> 00:28:59.393
of certain connections.

00:28:59.393 --> 00:29:02.368
So we thought let's look
at pruning in these PirB

00:29:02.368 --> 00:29:04.074
knockout mice.

00:29:04.074 --> 00:29:07.358
And to make a long story
short, what we discovered

00:29:07.358 --> 00:29:09.259
is that pruning is deficient.

00:29:09.259 --> 00:29:11.177
And the way we did this experiment

00:29:11.177 --> 00:29:14.298
was to label some of our
favorite neurons in the brain,

00:29:14.298 --> 00:29:15.615
these little green dots,

00:29:15.615 --> 00:29:17.533
with a green tracer substance.

00:29:17.533 --> 00:29:20.231
And then we could actually look at

00:29:20.231 --> 00:29:22.230
very high power over here.

00:29:22.230 --> 00:29:25.448
We could look at these
little protuberances,

00:29:25.448 --> 00:29:28.228
which are the sites of the synaptic inputs

00:29:28.228 --> 00:29:29.593
to these particular neurons,

00:29:29.593 --> 00:29:32.096
and then we could count them all.

00:29:32.096 --> 00:29:35.396
And when we did that
experiment in normal, wild-type

00:29:35.396 --> 00:29:37.541
versus PirB knockout mice,

00:29:37.541 --> 00:29:39.362
what we discovered is
that there were actually

00:29:39.362 --> 00:29:42.385
way more of these connections
in the knockout mice

00:29:42.385 --> 00:29:43.799
than in the wild-type mice,

00:29:43.799 --> 00:29:46.627
and that actually persisted
all the way into adulthood.

00:29:46.627 --> 00:29:49.244
And what we'd actually discovered is that

00:29:49.244 --> 00:29:53.486
somehow PirB is required
for synaptic pruning.

00:29:53.486 --> 00:29:56.900
And in the absence of PirB,
so in this knockout mouse,

00:29:56.900 --> 00:29:59.435
what we discovered is that
pruning was deficient,

00:29:59.435 --> 00:30:04.133
the see-saw went in favor
of synapse formation,

00:30:04.133 --> 00:30:08.180
genesis and stabilization, and
away from synaptic pruning.

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:10.130
Okay now there's a lot more
one could say about this

00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:12.162
but actually what I
really wanna talk about is

00:30:12.162 --> 00:30:15.137
boing, a light bulb went off for us,

00:30:15.137 --> 00:30:16.990
actually a few light
bulbs went off for us,

00:30:16.990 --> 00:30:18.647
but I wanna tell you about one.

00:30:18.647 --> 00:30:20.192
Here's the light bulb.

00:30:20.192 --> 00:30:23.946
The light bulb is that
in Alzheimer's disease,

00:30:23.946 --> 00:30:27.083
there's excessive synapse pruning.

00:30:27.083 --> 00:30:30.562
And this is thought to be
caused at least in part

00:30:30.562 --> 00:30:33.229
by these bad plaques and tangles

00:30:34.706 --> 00:30:39.420
that are formed by the
accumulation of a substance called

00:30:39.420 --> 00:30:42.920
Beta amyloid, which actually conglomerates

00:30:43.825 --> 00:30:46.474
to make very large plaques and tangles.

00:30:46.474 --> 00:30:48.831
And it's thought that this Beta amyloid

00:30:48.831 --> 00:30:52.862
is part of what's responsible
for loss of memory

00:30:52.862 --> 00:30:55.203
in Alzheimer's disease.

00:30:55.203 --> 00:30:58.340
So question is, is PirB involved

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:01.282
because remember PirB is
pruning is needed pruning

00:31:01.282 --> 00:31:04.077
and here we have too much
pruning in Alzheimer's disease.

00:31:04.077 --> 00:31:05.703
So how would you study that?

00:31:05.703 --> 00:31:08.352
Well we studied it in a large
variety of different ways,

00:31:08.352 --> 00:31:10.806
but the first way is PirB knockout mice,

00:31:10.806 --> 00:31:13.667
please meet Alzheimer's disease mice,

00:31:13.667 --> 00:31:15.244
so what do I mean by that?

00:31:15.244 --> 00:31:19.470
So neuroscientists can make
mouse models of disease,

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:22.964
and what they can do is they
can actually put into the mouse

00:31:22.964 --> 00:31:26.670
the human disease gene, the mutated gene,

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:29.872
and sadly for the mice,
but thank you mice,

00:31:29.872 --> 00:31:33.351
the mice can then end
up with a human disease.

00:31:33.351 --> 00:31:35.301
And in the case Alzheimer's mice,

00:31:35.301 --> 00:31:36.748
there are a variety of models,

00:31:36.748 --> 00:31:39.478
but in this case there are two genes

00:31:39.478 --> 00:31:43.396
that are known to cause early
onset family Alzheimer's.

00:31:43.396 --> 00:31:45.606
Both of these are put into the mouse,

00:31:45.606 --> 00:31:48.581
and the mouse, at about
nine months of age,

00:31:48.581 --> 00:31:51.490
gets the plaques and
tangles, and sadly also

00:31:51.490 --> 00:31:53.323
a serious memory loss.

00:31:54.513 --> 00:31:57.455
So what we did is we decided,

00:31:57.455 --> 00:31:59.991
let's see what happens if we removed PirB.

00:31:59.991 --> 00:32:02.299
Remember, if we remove PirB,

00:32:02.299 --> 00:32:05.078
then there's no pruning that happens.

00:32:05.078 --> 00:32:09.435
So what happens in Alzheimer's
mice that don't have PirB,

00:32:09.435 --> 00:32:12.344
and amazingly when we studied
their memory performance

00:32:12.344 --> 00:32:15.546
at nine months of age, they were protected

00:32:15.546 --> 00:32:20.276
from memory loss in the
absence of the PirB molecule,

00:32:20.276 --> 00:32:21.609
so that actually kinda makes sense,

00:32:21.609 --> 00:32:24.356
it's rather exciting
at least to me, it is.

00:32:24.356 --> 00:32:26.356
So how does this happen?

00:32:27.265 --> 00:32:29.980
So again to make another
really long story short,

00:32:29.980 --> 00:32:32.922
what we discovered is this PirB receptor

00:32:32.922 --> 00:32:36.422
is actually hijacked by this Beta amyloid,

00:32:37.408 --> 00:32:38.610
and what do I mean by hijacked?

00:32:38.610 --> 00:32:42.690
What I mean is, that PirB
as I said is a receptor,

00:32:42.690 --> 00:32:44.478
which always gets everybody excited

00:32:44.478 --> 00:32:46.087
in terms of making drugs.

00:32:46.087 --> 00:32:48.639
A receptor is a protein on a cell

00:32:48.639 --> 00:32:50.297
that does work for the cell.

00:32:50.297 --> 00:32:52.654
It takes information
from outside of the cell

00:32:52.654 --> 00:32:54.864
and it actually transfers that information

00:32:54.864 --> 00:32:57.888
to inside of the cell,
where it can do work.

00:32:57.888 --> 00:32:59.350
And in the case of PirB,

00:32:59.350 --> 00:33:02.731
that information is part
of the pruning process.

00:33:02.731 --> 00:33:05.218
And there are normal ligands for PirB,

00:33:05.218 --> 00:33:07.510
including this thing called MHC Class One.

00:33:07.510 --> 00:33:10.501
So what we think is happening
is that Beta amyloid

00:33:10.501 --> 00:33:12.988
is also binding to this PirB molecule

00:33:12.988 --> 00:33:15.816
and driving pruning to excess.

00:33:15.816 --> 00:33:17.766
So the other point I wanna make

00:33:17.766 --> 00:33:22.155
is that it turns out that
there are actually human

00:33:22.155 --> 00:33:25.243
homologues of PirB, there
are quite a number of them,

00:33:25.243 --> 00:33:27.356
and what we discovered
is that one of them,

00:33:27.356 --> 00:33:28.819
called another mouthful,

00:33:28.819 --> 00:33:30.054
I'm not even gonna write it out for you,

00:33:30.054 --> 00:33:34.137
it's called LilrB2, so
it's very similar to PirB,

00:33:35.516 --> 00:33:38.880
and this human homologue is also binds,

00:33:38.880 --> 00:33:42.082
it seems to be hijacked by
the PirB, by Beta amyloid,

00:33:42.082 --> 00:33:46.064
and it's also present
in the human forebrain

00:33:46.064 --> 00:33:50.762
and the signaling caused
by binding of Beta amyloid

00:33:50.762 --> 00:33:52.956
seems to be also derailed in the same way

00:33:52.956 --> 00:33:55.866
the human Alzheimer brain
as it is in the mouse brain.

00:33:55.866 --> 00:33:57.670
Okay so now I'm gonna summarize.

00:33:57.670 --> 00:34:02.192
Okay so what I've suggested
is that Alzheimer's disease,

00:34:02.192 --> 00:34:05.357
which is thought to be a
problem of synapse pruning

00:34:05.357 --> 00:34:09.404
may be driven by Beta
amyloid-PirB interactions,

00:34:09.404 --> 00:34:11.143
definitely worth following that up.

00:34:11.143 --> 00:34:14.638
So pruning is accelerated in this case,

00:34:14.638 --> 00:34:17.221
and what it also suggests to us

00:34:18.555 --> 00:34:20.961
is there might a pill in there after all.

00:34:20.961 --> 00:34:24.976
And what's great is that we
could even maybe make a pill

00:34:24.976 --> 00:34:26.975
based on the fact that
there's a receptor here,

00:34:26.975 --> 00:34:29.315
we know exactly what to do, and in fact,

00:34:29.315 --> 00:34:32.030
we have made a little pill
and tried it out in mice

00:34:32.030 --> 00:34:36.841
and so the last point I
wanna make is stay tuned.

00:34:36.841 --> 00:34:39.344
So I think it's really interesting

00:34:39.344 --> 00:34:43.301
that PirB or LilrB
blockade might represent

00:34:43.301 --> 00:34:46.577
a slightly different therapeutic approach

00:34:46.577 --> 00:34:47.715
for treating Alzheimer's,

00:34:47.715 --> 00:34:49.877
but maybe also other pruning disorders.

00:34:49.877 --> 00:34:52.169
Now this might be good in the sense that

00:34:52.169 --> 00:34:53.761
I don't know if you read recently,

00:34:53.761 --> 00:34:56.167
but there was another
failure of another major

00:34:56.167 --> 00:34:59.084
Lilly Alzheimer disease drug trial,

00:35:00.133 --> 00:35:02.295
so it's really, I'm getting older,

00:35:02.295 --> 00:35:04.310
I would really like something soon.

00:35:04.310 --> 00:35:07.415
I want these trials to succeed.

00:35:07.415 --> 00:35:08.536
But maybe there's a pill,

00:35:08.536 --> 00:35:10.828
but even more interesting I think is

00:35:10.828 --> 00:35:14.095
that in fact lessons from
neural development may offer

00:35:14.095 --> 00:35:16.647
new treatment avenues
for Alzheimer's disease

00:35:16.647 --> 00:35:17.720
and other pruning disorders.

00:35:17.720 --> 00:35:19.898
So with that I just wanna thank everyone.

00:35:19.898 --> 00:35:23.149
Thank you all, and also I
wanna thank our organizers

00:35:23.149 --> 00:35:26.253
and I have to remind
everyone that this experiment

00:35:26.253 --> 00:35:28.496
was done, these kinds of experiments,

00:35:28.496 --> 00:35:31.698
with many many students and
colleagues, and someone,

00:35:31.698 --> 00:35:33.941
and I would also like to thank the mice.

00:35:33.941 --> 00:35:35.524
So thanks everyone.

