00:40:24.691 --> 00:40:29.356
And, or a young kitten I guess,
I'm not sure what (laughs)

00:40:29.356 --> 00:40:31.209
would be the proper way of putting it.

00:40:31.209 --> 00:40:36.150
When she made a very important (laughs)

00:40:36.150 --> 00:40:40.067
sorry Carla (laughing).

00:40:40.067 --> 00:40:44.017
It was a very important observation about

00:40:44.017 --> 00:40:45.301
traveling waves in the retina,

00:40:45.301 --> 00:40:47.219
the reason why it's
important is that these occur

00:40:47.219 --> 00:40:49.088
even before the eye opens.

00:40:49.088 --> 00:40:51.510
So those dynamic patterns
of activity that are

00:40:51.510 --> 00:40:53.639
already spreading through the retina.

00:40:53.639 --> 00:40:56.061
And here you can see,

00:40:56.061 --> 00:40:57.881
this is now from a more recent paper,

00:40:57.881 --> 00:41:00.728
but this is from an array of
electrodes that are put on

00:41:00.728 --> 00:41:02.367
the retina, that's slapped down

00:41:02.367 --> 00:41:04.188
and these are the action potentials

00:41:04.188 --> 00:41:05.764
coming from the ganglion cells.

00:41:05.764 --> 00:41:07.357
And you can see over seconds,

00:41:07.357 --> 00:41:09.194
this wave of activity
sweeps across the retina,

00:41:09.194 --> 00:41:11.616
now why is that interesting,

00:41:11.616 --> 00:41:14.151
well it turns out that this,

00:41:14.151 --> 00:41:16.281
these waves are giving
a temporal structure

00:41:16.281 --> 00:41:18.784
to the action potentials
going up to the next stage

00:41:18.784 --> 00:41:19.946
in the lateral geniculate,

00:41:19.946 --> 00:41:22.329
and it's essential for
getting that pathway

00:41:22.329 --> 00:41:23.954
wired up properly.

00:41:23.954 --> 00:41:26.587
Being able to sort out the
input from the two eyes,

00:41:26.587 --> 00:41:28.457
first of all, 'cause the
waves are independent,

00:41:28.457 --> 00:41:30.488
but secondly there's
information about location

00:41:30.488 --> 00:41:35.193
because as the waves spreads
from one location to the next,

00:41:35.193 --> 00:41:39.037
the action potentials arrive
one position to the next

00:41:39.037 --> 00:41:42.270
and that helps sort out the map in LGN

00:41:42.270 --> 00:41:45.228
and ultimately into the cortex.

00:41:45.228 --> 00:41:47.811
Now very recently we discovered

00:41:49.763 --> 00:41:52.180
waves in the cerebral cortex.

00:41:53.973 --> 00:41:55.550
Global waves.

00:41:55.550 --> 00:41:59.694
Unbelievably large scale
patterns of activity

00:41:59.694 --> 00:42:03.482
that we still don't understand
the significance of,

00:42:03.482 --> 00:42:05.692
although I have a pretty good hypothesis.

00:42:05.692 --> 00:42:08.975
And they occur while you are sleeping.

00:42:08.975 --> 00:42:11.218
When you go to sleep, you
go through several stages

00:42:11.218 --> 00:42:13.949
from awake down to deep slow wave sleep,

00:42:13.949 --> 00:42:15.640
but on the way you go through stage two,

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:17.557
what's called intermediate sleep,

00:42:17.557 --> 00:42:20.272
and it's characterized
by these sleep spindles.

00:42:20.272 --> 00:42:23.571
These are bursting activity
that originates in the thalamus,

00:42:23.571 --> 00:42:25.311
projects to the cortex.

00:42:25.311 --> 00:42:28.025
They are 10 to 14 Hertz,

00:42:28.025 --> 00:42:29.358
they last one or two seconds,

00:42:29.358 --> 00:42:31.357
they recur every five seconds,

00:42:31.357 --> 00:42:32.349
and there are some people who spend

00:42:32.349 --> 00:42:35.892
up to half of the night
in this slow wave sleep,

00:42:35.892 --> 00:42:38.964
during which the spindles are occurring.

00:42:38.964 --> 00:42:42.052
Now I've done some very
detailed biophysical modeling,

00:42:42.052 --> 00:42:44.507
so I can tell you precise mechanisms

00:42:44.507 --> 00:42:47.351
that give rise to the
spindles, it's a bursting,

00:42:47.351 --> 00:42:50.423
it has to do with new ion
channels that are uncovered

00:42:50.423 --> 00:42:52.840
when the cells hyperpolarize,

00:42:53.674 --> 00:42:56.161
it means the membrane potential goes down.

00:42:56.161 --> 00:42:58.583
But what I would have never guessed

00:42:58.583 --> 00:43:03.264
is how the activity between
the thalamus and the cortex

00:43:03.264 --> 00:43:07.246
organizes itself, in the
textbooks what you hear is

00:43:07.246 --> 00:43:09.310
that it's synchronous,
that is to say it occurs

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:10.480
at the same place in the cortex

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:12.090
at exactly the same time.

00:43:12.090 --> 00:43:14.008
And it is approximately synchronous.

00:43:14.008 --> 00:43:16.186
But I wanted to let
you decide for yourself

00:43:16.186 --> 00:43:18.152
how synchronous it really is.

00:43:18.152 --> 00:43:20.347
So this is an array of
electrodes, eight by eight

00:43:20.347 --> 00:43:23.191
64 electrodes that have
been placed on a surface

00:43:23.191 --> 00:43:26.003
of the cortex in an epilepsy patient,

00:43:26.003 --> 00:43:28.506
who has been, gone to the hospital with

00:43:28.506 --> 00:43:32.131
a form of epilepsy that can't
be treated with any drugs.

00:43:32.131 --> 00:43:34.504
And so what they have to
do is isolate the focus

00:43:34.504 --> 00:43:37.251
so they can go in and
take it out and hopefully

00:43:37.251 --> 00:43:41.217
keep that epilepsy, the person,
from having seizures again.

00:43:41.217 --> 00:43:43.460
So here's the electrodes,
and by the way they have

00:43:43.460 --> 00:43:45.784
these electrodes in for about a week,

00:43:45.784 --> 00:43:47.117
waiting for a seizure to occur,

00:43:47.117 --> 00:43:50.546
so it's a fantastic opportunity
for someone like me,

00:43:50.546 --> 00:43:52.708
a neuroscientist who wants
to ask fundamental questions

00:43:52.708 --> 00:43:54.740
about a human brain.

00:43:54.740 --> 00:43:56.658
About things like language,
for which there was

00:43:56.658 --> 00:43:59.324
no other model system.

00:43:59.324 --> 00:44:02.916
Okay so what we've done
is color each in gray

00:44:02.916 --> 00:44:04.583
from white to black.

00:44:06.052 --> 00:44:07.921
As you can see, the amplitude.

00:44:07.921 --> 00:44:10.424
And this is the one that
you're gonna see here in red

00:44:10.424 --> 00:44:13.057
is this one, but all the other electrodes

00:44:13.057 --> 00:44:15.398
are gonna be represented that way.

00:44:15.398 --> 00:44:19.936
And I want you just to
follow the white dots.

00:44:19.936 --> 00:44:22.853
And tell me what pattern they form.

00:44:28.311 --> 00:44:30.928
This is going around one
77 milliseconds right,

00:44:30.928 --> 00:44:34.595
so this is going around
at roughly 14 Hertz.

00:44:36.357 --> 00:44:39.607
And you can see as it goes up and down,

00:44:42.322 --> 00:44:44.989
so did everybody see what I saw?

00:44:46.028 --> 00:44:49.361
It's a rotating circular traveling wave.

00:44:51.099 --> 00:44:52.627
And it's global.

00:44:52.627 --> 00:44:54.512
It goes from, as you can see,

00:44:54.512 --> 00:44:57.145
it goes form the temporal
cortex to the parietal cortex

00:44:57.145 --> 00:44:59.356
up to the prefrontal cortex.

00:44:59.356 --> 00:45:02.542
And if you look at the pattern
on the side of my head,

00:45:02.542 --> 00:45:04.915
this should remind you of Princess Leia.

00:45:04.915 --> 00:45:07.165
(laughing)

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:10.636
Now what are these...

00:45:10.636 --> 00:45:12.012
So this of course occurs
thousands of times

00:45:12.012 --> 00:45:13.431
during the night, what are they doing?

00:45:13.431 --> 00:45:15.853
We think it has something to
do with synaptic plasticity.

00:45:15.853 --> 00:45:18.129
Because the timing is just
right for something called

00:45:18.129 --> 00:45:20.177
spike time dependent plasticity.

00:45:20.177 --> 00:45:22.793
And so it may be that
we know there's replay

00:45:22.793 --> 00:45:24.874
from the hippocampus during the night.

00:45:24.874 --> 00:45:26.841
It's called memory consolidation

00:45:26.841 --> 00:45:28.905
and it occurs over many many nights

00:45:28.905 --> 00:45:30.449
and this might be the mechanism.

00:45:30.449 --> 00:45:32.692
So we have a really great opportunity here

00:45:32.692 --> 00:45:34.609
to actually explore it.

00:45:36.122 --> 00:45:39.373
Now we know that there are connections,

00:45:39.373 --> 00:45:41.274
long range connections
between different parts

00:45:41.274 --> 00:45:43.566
of the cortex, these are
called association fibers,

00:45:43.566 --> 00:45:46.996
and also across between the hemispheres.

00:45:46.996 --> 00:45:50.913
And it's really these
that we think are carrying

00:45:50.913 --> 00:45:53.383
the time delay signals,
and it may be that these

00:45:53.383 --> 00:45:55.724
time delays are really
important to getting them right.

00:45:55.724 --> 00:45:59.170
We know that for example
in traumatic brain injury

00:45:59.170 --> 00:46:02.209
when soldiers come back
from the Middle East

00:46:02.209 --> 00:46:05.292
with traumatic, problems with trauma,

00:46:06.289 --> 00:46:08.971
they often have problems
with concentration

00:46:08.971 --> 00:46:12.693
and attention, and concussions
on football players

00:46:12.693 --> 00:46:15.521
and so forth, and when you
look in the brain with MR,

00:46:15.521 --> 00:46:16.805
the only thing you can find

00:46:16.805 --> 00:46:18.350
are little spots of the white matter,

00:46:18.350 --> 00:46:20.934
so it could well be that the white matter

00:46:20.934 --> 00:46:23.226
is really important for
integrating globally

00:46:23.226 --> 00:46:25.518
all the information,
different parts of the cortex,

00:46:25.518 --> 00:46:28.394
and it could be that by
strengthening connections

00:46:28.394 --> 00:46:31.759
between these distant
areas through spindles

00:46:31.759 --> 00:46:32.848
or some other mechanism

00:46:32.848 --> 00:46:36.099
that we're able to connect
up all the different parts

00:46:36.099 --> 00:46:38.261
of the sensory cortices and association

00:46:38.261 --> 00:46:40.813
in the prefrontal cortex.

00:46:40.813 --> 00:46:42.646
Now the timing is also

00:46:45.055 --> 00:46:47.282
obviously very important
in the auditory cortex

00:46:47.282 --> 00:46:48.501
and the motor systems,

00:46:48.501 --> 00:46:52.207
so this is I think something
it hasn't been explored,

00:46:52.207 --> 00:46:54.612
we focus so much on the gray matter

00:46:54.612 --> 00:46:56.270
and not so much on the white matter.

00:46:56.270 --> 00:46:59.098
There are some really
intriguing observations

00:46:59.098 --> 00:47:02.868
that when learning takes place,
it's not just the synapses

00:47:02.868 --> 00:47:04.266
that change their strength,

00:47:04.266 --> 00:47:06.526
the volume of the white matter changes.

00:47:06.526 --> 00:47:08.151
How could that be?

00:47:08.151 --> 00:47:12.318
Well the oligdendrocytes
that wrap around the axons

00:47:14.116 --> 00:47:16.164
change the speed, so
maybe what's happening

00:47:16.164 --> 00:47:19.009
is you're adjusting
the timing of the spike

00:47:19.009 --> 00:47:23.170
as it goes across these
large scale connections

00:47:23.170 --> 00:47:25.218
between two different parts of the cortex.

00:47:25.218 --> 00:47:27.558
That's all speculative but
I think it really means

00:47:27.558 --> 00:47:30.386
we have to start looking
carefully at the axons

00:47:30.386 --> 00:47:32.467
as well as the dendrites.

00:47:32.467 --> 00:47:36.823
Now I'm gonna play a science
fiction movie for you.

00:47:36.823 --> 00:47:40.990
It's an animated, but it's
based on the connections we see

00:47:42.089 --> 00:47:44.414
and it's also, it gives you,
you'll see an impression

00:47:44.414 --> 00:47:46.413
of the activity that might be taking place

00:47:46.413 --> 00:47:47.794
within the cortex.

00:47:47.794 --> 00:47:50.211
So these little white flashes

00:47:53.044 --> 00:47:55.450
are actually action potentials, spikes,

00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:57.661
going down the axons that you just saw

00:47:57.661 --> 00:48:00.115
between these different cortical areas.

00:48:00.115 --> 00:48:01.740
And this gives you an
impression of what it might be

00:48:01.740 --> 00:48:05.186
if you could actually see into your brain.

00:48:05.186 --> 00:48:08.990
You know, the person sitting next to you,

00:48:08.990 --> 00:48:12.387
and actually see what they're thinking.

00:48:12.387 --> 00:48:16.554
Or what they're seeing, or
what it is that they're doing

00:48:17.523 --> 00:48:22.090
in terms of their motor
system, every single thought

00:48:22.090 --> 00:48:24.512
is gonna be represented by
some pattern of activity

00:48:24.512 --> 00:48:26.934
in some part of your
brain, and specifically

00:48:26.934 --> 00:48:30.087
in different parts of the cortex.

00:48:30.087 --> 00:48:34.254
Now, right now, this is
science fiction for the human,

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:38.977
but, on April 2nd 2013,

00:48:41.888 --> 00:48:44.358
Obama announced this grand initiative,

00:48:44.358 --> 00:48:46.894
this only, these grand
initiatives only occur

00:48:46.894 --> 00:48:49.673
once every decade or two.

00:48:49.673 --> 00:48:52.014
And when they do, it really has an impact.

00:48:52.014 --> 00:48:54.842
And it has had a huge impact
in the neuroscience community

00:48:54.842 --> 00:48:57.178
over the last three years.

00:48:57.178 --> 00:49:01.116
The key letters by the
way in the acronym, IN,

00:49:01.116 --> 00:49:03.148
is innovative neurotechnology.

00:49:03.148 --> 00:49:06.886
And I have to say that our
sponsors, the Kavli Foundation,

00:49:06.886 --> 00:49:11.389
were critically important
in bringing this opportunity

00:49:11.389 --> 00:49:14.135
to the notice of the White House,

00:49:14.135 --> 00:49:16.980
and Miyoung Chung in
particular was the spark plug

00:49:16.980 --> 00:49:18.670
who actually got the thing off the ground,

00:49:18.670 --> 00:49:20.133
so we really owe the Kavli Foundation

00:49:20.133 --> 00:49:22.214
a great debt of gratitude.

00:49:22.214 --> 00:49:25.123
But what's happened
since this announcement

00:49:25.123 --> 00:49:28.309
is really astonishing because
new tools and techniques

00:49:28.309 --> 00:49:31.348
are coming online that
are accelerating research

00:49:31.348 --> 00:49:35.249
by orders of magnitude, and
let me give you one example.

00:49:35.249 --> 00:49:37.379
And this is not science fiction.

00:49:37.379 --> 00:49:38.462
This is real.

00:49:39.540 --> 00:49:43.707
This, you are seeing a zebra
fish in a larval brain.

00:49:45.002 --> 00:49:48.090
You can see it's not, it's
only a millimeter or so across.

00:49:48.090 --> 00:49:50.252
Contains about 80,000 neurons.

00:49:50.252 --> 00:49:54.575
It has a genetic marker that
will light the neuron up

00:49:54.575 --> 00:49:57.160
when it's activated,
see here's the neuron,

00:49:57.160 --> 00:50:00.492
here's the neuron, these
are the ones that are firing

00:50:00.492 --> 00:50:02.442
at this particular moment in time.

00:50:02.442 --> 00:50:05.612
And this is looking at it
from below, from above,

00:50:05.612 --> 00:50:07.660
from the front and from the side.

00:50:07.660 --> 00:50:11.740
We can record from all the
neurons at the same time

00:50:11.740 --> 00:50:14.259
from this brain, okay?

00:50:14.259 --> 00:50:18.092
And I'm gonna play a
movie just to prove that.

00:50:21.476 --> 00:50:24.694
Now I have to tell you
this zebra fish larva

00:50:24.694 --> 00:50:27.343
is just sitting there, it's immobilized.

00:50:27.343 --> 00:50:30.383
And there's no sensory
input, there's no light.

00:50:30.383 --> 00:50:33.812
So what you're seeing is
called spontaneous activity.

00:50:33.812 --> 00:50:37.778
But every once in a while,
the spontaneous activity,

00:50:37.778 --> 00:50:40.314
the pattern changes like
right there, what's happening?

00:50:40.314 --> 00:50:43.321
Something happened in the
brain of the zebra fish

00:50:43.321 --> 00:50:46.165
that is unrelated to
anything that the zebra fish

00:50:46.165 --> 00:50:49.332
is experiencing or is actually moving.

00:50:51.253 --> 00:50:53.086
But it's really clear,

00:50:56.210 --> 00:50:59.721
to me at least, that we don't
understand the first thing.

00:50:59.721 --> 00:51:01.971
(laughing)

00:51:03.682 --> 00:51:07.849
And as a Chinese curse, may
you get what you wish for,

00:51:09.002 --> 00:51:11.180
and this is something we've always wanted

00:51:11.180 --> 00:51:14.138
to be able to have access
to all of the neurons

00:51:14.138 --> 00:51:15.845
and the activity occurring,

00:51:15.845 --> 00:51:17.714
I mean for all we know, the zebra fish,

00:51:17.714 --> 00:51:19.957
this is what the zebra
fish does when it thinks,

00:51:19.957 --> 00:51:21.534
I mean what do you do when
you go to bed at night

00:51:21.534 --> 00:51:23.777
and you're sitting there right.

00:51:23.777 --> 00:51:25.955
There's no sensory input
coming, you're not moving,

00:51:25.955 --> 00:51:27.402
but thoughts go through your head right?

00:51:27.402 --> 00:51:29.157
I mean so that's gotta
be represented somewhere,

00:51:29.157 --> 00:51:32.457
so this is getting tools
and techniques that allow us

00:51:32.457 --> 00:51:35.025
to decode what those patterns are,

00:51:35.025 --> 00:51:37.690
it's really the challenge.

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:40.828
And we're very fortunate
that tools and techniques

00:51:40.828 --> 00:51:44.046
are coming online exactly
when we needed them.

00:51:44.046 --> 00:51:45.590
It's called machine learning,

00:51:45.590 --> 00:51:48.077
and there's a meeting that's
been held for the last 30 years

00:51:48.077 --> 00:51:51.084
called Neural Information
Processing Systems, NIPS,

00:51:51.084 --> 00:51:55.082
and the next meeting will be
held in Barcelona next week.

00:51:55.082 --> 00:51:57.249
6,000 people will show up.

00:51:58.447 --> 00:52:00.544
At the first meeting there was 600,

00:52:00.544 --> 00:52:03.339
so it's a factor of 10 greater,

00:52:03.339 --> 00:52:05.924
and every single high
tech company is showing up

00:52:05.924 --> 00:52:08.037
to recruit and why, it turns out that

00:52:08.037 --> 00:52:10.654
these tools and techniques
that have been developed

00:52:10.654 --> 00:52:14.821
and have been inspired by
the brain, the N is neural,

00:52:16.326 --> 00:52:19.024
turns out have fantastic
applications to the real world,

00:52:19.024 --> 00:52:20.373
you've heard about deep learning,

00:52:20.373 --> 00:52:23.526
well deep learning came
from this NIPS community.

00:52:23.526 --> 00:52:26.858
And those same tools and
techniques can be used

00:52:26.858 --> 00:52:29.605
for understanding those
patterns of activity

00:52:29.605 --> 00:52:32.807
that you just saw for analyzing,
large scale recordings,

00:52:32.807 --> 00:52:35.863
for working out the
detailed wiring diagram

00:52:35.863 --> 00:52:39.747
called connectomics, and
for quantifying behavior.

00:52:39.747 --> 00:52:43.778
Turns out that we can
go way beyond the simple

00:52:43.778 --> 00:52:45.566
having an animal press a button

00:52:45.566 --> 00:52:47.354
with having it move around freely.

00:52:47.354 --> 00:52:51.466
And this can be done
automatically and scored

00:52:51.466 --> 00:52:56.244
and it's been done on flies,
it's been done on mice,

00:52:56.244 --> 00:52:58.536
they have a sequence
of stereotype behavior,

00:52:58.536 --> 00:53:00.665
they groom themselves and so forth,

00:53:00.665 --> 00:53:02.291
and interestingly on humans.

00:53:02.291 --> 00:53:05.883
We can now detect and automatically score

00:53:05.883 --> 00:53:07.508
your facial expressions.

00:53:07.508 --> 00:53:10.093
Like we saw some pictures
of the fearful face,

00:53:10.093 --> 00:53:11.426
well we've worked with Paul Eckman

00:53:11.426 --> 00:53:13.392
and we've developed
these deep learning tools

00:53:13.392 --> 00:53:15.635
to actually be able to
do that automatically

00:53:15.635 --> 00:53:18.545
and we can detect these
fleeting moments of expression

00:53:18.545 --> 00:53:21.129
across your face, they're
called micro-expressions.

00:53:21.129 --> 00:53:23.665
And they're very telling
because they're brain leaks,

00:53:23.665 --> 00:53:26.591
they're feelings you're having
inside that leak through

00:53:26.591 --> 00:53:28.460
and you may not even be
aware of them yourself,

00:53:28.460 --> 00:53:30.960
but they can be picked up now.

00:53:32.052 --> 00:53:34.880
And that could be a way
that we can understand

00:53:34.880 --> 00:53:39.204
